text.section:
The board may refuse to issue a license or suspend, revoke, impose probationary conditions upon, impose an administrative fine, issue a written reprimand, or any combination thereof regarding any licensee upon proof that the licensee has:
Been convicted of a crime as described in KRS 335B.010(4) or an offense that otherwise directly relates to the occupation of interpreter. A plea of "no contest" may be treated as a conviction for purposes of disciplinary action;
Knowingly misrepresented or concealed a material fact in obtaining a license or in reinstatement thereof;
Committed any fraudulent act or practice;
Been incompetent or negligent in the practice of interpreting;
Violated any state statute or administrative regulation governing the practice of interpreting;
Violated the code of ethics of the national organization issuing the licensee's certification as incorporated in administrative regulation; or
Violated any federal or state law considered by the board to be applicable to the practice of interpreting.
